P4 Explore and Summarize Data

M.J. van der Poel

April 11th 2017

Red Wine Quality

This tidy data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

The guiding question in this investigation is Which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines?

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests):
1 - fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
2 - volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
3 - citric acid (g / dm^3)
4 - residual sugar (g / dm^3)
5 - chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3)
6 - free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
7 - total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
8 - density (g / cm^3)
9 - pH
10 - sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
11 - alcohol (% by volume)

Output variable (based on sensory data):
12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Description of attributes:
1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines
4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet
5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine
6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine
7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine
8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale
10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant
11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data):
12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Total sulfur dioxide is an addition of free and bound sulfite. Created a separate column to present the bound sulfur by substracting free from the total sulfur.

The dataset consists of 12 variables, with 1599 observations. There are no missing values and the dataset is structured and tidy. X is the unique key that identifies each wine. All the other fields except quality are quantitive measurements for that wine. Quality is a qualitive field at the ordinal level. I therefore changed the integer values into factors ranging from 3 up and until 8.

Most wines have a fixed acidity between 4 and 12 g / dm^3 with a mean of 8,32. The distribution is normal and a little bit right skewed. Outliers on the right. 1st Quartile = 7.1 g / dm^3 Median = 7.9 g / dm^3 3rd Quartile = 9.2 g / dm^3 Mean = 8.316 g / dm^3

Volatile acidity seems to behave like a bimodal distribution with most values between 0.2 and 1.00 g / dm^3, and with a peak at around 0.4 and 0.6 g / dm^3. Outliers on the right. 1st Quartile = 0.39 g / dm^3 Median = 0.52 g / dm^3 3rd Quartile = 0.64 g / dm^3 Mean = 0.5274 g / dm^3

The citric acid is more or less evenly distributed between 0.02 and 0.5 g / dm^3 and then drops lineair until 0.78 g / dm^3. 1st Quartile = 0.09 g / dm^3 Median = 0.26 g / dm^3 3rd Quartile = 0.42 g / dm^3 Mean = 0.2698 g / dm^3

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 observations of red wines in the dataset with 12 features (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol % and quality).

All variables except quality are quantitive, continuous variables. Quality is an ordered variable with the following levels from worst to best: 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8.

Other observations:

  • Sulfur dioxides have a normal distribution on a log10 scale
  • Citric acid is more or less evenly distributed between 0.02 and 0.5 g / dm^3 and then drops lineair until 0.78 g / dm^3.
  • Alcohol percentage quickly builds from 9 percent up to a peak at 9.5 percent and then drops lineairly to zero at around 14 percent.
  • Volatile acidity seems to behave like a bimodal distribution.
  • The mean and the median are almost equal for Ph and density.
  • All other continuous variables have a normal distribution with some skewness.
  • 82.5 % of the wines have a quality of 5 or 6. 1,75% has a quality of 3 or 8.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature in the dataset is quality. I would like to determine Which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines. I expect that quality is at least determined by the right combination of sweetness (residual sugar and alcohol) and sourness (fixe and volatile acidity, citric acid and PH).

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The relation between alcohol and residual sugar is interesting because alcohol is formed during fermentation of sugar. The remaining sugar influences the sweetness of the wine. Another important taste influencer is acidity expressed in the three types of acid(ity) and PH. Finally the tanin determines the dryness. Tannin is not measured, but just like free sulfur dioxide, it acts as an anti oxidant. Lower levels of free sulfur dioxide could indicate higher (not measured) levels of tannin.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created bound.sulfur.dioxide by subtracting free.sulfur.dioxide from total.sulfur.dioxide. At first I factorised quality with #RW\(quality<-factor(RW\)quality, levels=c(3,4,5,6,7,8), ordered = TRUE), but changed it back because it gave errors with the cor function when I wanted to correlate quality with the other fields.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Total sulphur dioxide has two ourliers that I removed. Alcohol had one outlier that I removed.

I used the following guidelines for correlation: If > 0,7 = Large, 0,7 - 0,5 is Moderate, 0,5 - 0,3 small but meaningfull.

Based on this I see a moderate positive correlation between:
* fixed acidity and citric acid
* fixed acidity and density

I see a moderate negative correlation between:
* fixed acidity and PH
* volatile acidity and citric acid
* citric acid and PH
* alcohol and density

I see meaningfull positive correlation between:
* citric acid and density
* citric acid and sulphates
* residual sugar and density
* chlorides and sulphates
* free sulfur dioxide and bound sulfur dioxode
* quality and alcohol

I see meaningfull negative correlation between:
* quality and volatile acidity
* PH and density

I on purpose did not mention the correlation between bound and free sulfur dioxide on the one hand and total dioxide on the other hand.

While citric acid and fixed acidity are strongly positively correlated (+0.68), volatile acidity is negatively correlated with the other two (-0.27 and -0.56).

Volitale acidity has an almost lineair influence on quality, with no distinction between quality level 7 and 8. Citric acids influence on quality is not lineair , but the citric acids level makes jumps between every two quality levels. There are three groups: quality levels 3 and 4, 5 and 6, 7 and 8. Within the groups citric acids level is more or less stable, between the groups levels make a jump.

pH is very strongly influenced by fixed acidity (clear direction, close to the smooth line, correlation -0.69),a little bit less strong (data points more spread out) by citric acid (-0.54), and the least by volatile acidity (+0.24). More fixed acidity and citric acid add to the overal acidity taste, more volatile acidity to less overal acidity taste.

From the correlation information and the boxplots it is clear that acidity, acid and PH are strongly correlated to each other. But, is it the volatile acidity (-0.39) and the citric acid (+0.23) that are correlated to quality. The box plots for these two show that higher levels of citric acid and lower levels of volatile acid on average lead to a higher quality. What is also noticable, that for quality levels 7 and 8, there is hardly any difference. Maybe to discriminate between a 7 and 8, other factors play a more important role. For fixed acidity I dont see significant differences on level 5 and 6 and no trend taking the other levels into account. I suppose this is because the the majority of measurements is on level 5 and 6. A higher fixed acidity does lead to a lower PH. Higher quality wines tend to lower PH levels.

I cannot discover any relation between residual sugar and quality. The median for the various quality levels is not moving in a certain direction and there are lots of outliers for most quality levels.

Free and bound (and therefore total) sulfur dioxide does not show a linear relationship with quality, but a normal-like distribution: low levels of SO2 for low and high quality wines and higher levels of SO2 for the average quality wines. I wonder if in the right combination with other variables like alcohol, sulphates and/or PH, SO2 can improve or worsen a wine.

Although density has a correlation with quality, I believe this is caused by the effect that primarily alcohol and fixed acidity have on density. Alcohol lowers the density, residual sugar, citric acid and fixed acidity raises the density.

Higher quality wines have more sulphates on average. Between quality 7 and 8 sulphates are not a discriminating factor anymore.

Alcohol has the strongest and positive correlation with quality (+0.48). I notice a strange dip in what seems a linear relation between the two at quality level 5, both for mean and median. Is that because the SO2 amount at quality level 5 is very high compared to the other quality levels? You could also look at it as follows from quality level 5 till 8 there is a lineair raise in quality with the alcohol %. The same form level 3 till 4. But from 3 till 4 the raise is less steep and the mean and median % is higher then 5.

Bivariate Analysis

How did the feature of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

The feature of interest is quality. I found a 5 interesting correlations in order of their magnitude:

  1. Alcohol %: Highest correlation with quality of +0.48. Higher quality wines on average have higher alcohol levels, but there is a dip on quality level 5. I wonder if this dip can be explained by the high SO2 levels on quality level 5. I checked quality level 5 for the other variables and PH shows a simular, though difficult to see, dip. I want to examine alcohol, bound SO2, PH and quality with one another.
  2. Volatile Acidity: Correlation -0.39. Higher quality wines tend to have lower volitale acidity levels. Again, between quality levels 7 and 8 I dont see much difference, except that the standard deviation for level 8 is smaller.
  3. Sulphates: Correlation +0.25. Higher quality wines tend to have higher sulphates levels. Between quality levels 7 and 8 the median level is the same, but the standard deviation on level 8 is much smaller.
  4. Citric Acid: Correlation +0.23. Higher quality wines tend to have higher citric acid levels. Between quality levels 7 and 8 I dont see much difference.
  5. Bound Sulphur Dioxide: Correlation -0.21. I calculated the bound SO2 by removing the free SO2 from the total SO2. The bound SO2 has the strongest correlation with quality of the three. They all have a normal distribution, meaning that both low and high quality wines have on average low levels of SO2 and medium quality wines have high levels of SO2.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features?

I expected that Citric acid and fixed acidity would have a negative correlation with ph, I didnt expect volatile acidity to have a positive correlation. I think, that in this case it is relative, meaning, they all contribute to the acidity levels, but volatile acidity contributes much less, and therefore contibutes to Ph levels on the high end of the range.

Density has a relation with four variables: Alcohol lowers the density, residual sugar, citric acid and fixed acidity raises the density.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relation I found was between total SO2 and bound SO2. But since I derived bound SO2 from total SO2, this is no real surprise.

The next strongest relation I found between PH and fixed acidity (-0.68).

The strongest relation I found with the feature of interest quality was with alcohol (+0.48).

Multivariate Analysis

Bound sulfur dioxide and alcohol vs quality

Bound sulfur dioxide levels bigger than around 25mg per dm^3 seem to raise the quality level of wines containing lower % level of alcohol. Between quality levels 4 and 5 there is a slight drop in average alcohol %, but there is a bigger spread in bound sulfur dioxide. At level 6, the spread of sulfur dioxide is again smaller, but from this point on, alcohol % starts rising.

Lineair multivariable model

the lineiar multivariable model for the wine quality is as follows:

Quality = 0.837 + (0.293 * alcohol %) - (1.198 * volatile acidity) + (0.748 * sulphates) - (0.024 * citric acid) - (0.004 * bound sulfur dioxide)

The model does not take into account the how the relation between higher bound sulfur dioxide levels and lower alchol % can influence the wine quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The first plot shows the distribution of the 1599 red wines in the dataset. The larger part of the wines fall in quality levels 5 or 6 (more than 80 %). The number of wines at the highest and the lowest quality level are very low (less than 2 %).

Plot Two

Description Two

In order of their correlation with quality, the five features with the highest correlation are shown. All features except bound SO2 show a linear relationship with quality. Alcohol % shows a dip in at quality level 5 in its linear relationship with quality where bound SO2 shows a peak.

In order of their correlation the following features influence quality:
* Alcohol
* Volatile acidity
* Sulphates

Bound SO2 seems to boost the quality of red wine when alcohol % is low.

Plot Three

Description Three

Bound sulfur dioxide levels bigger than around 25mg per dm^3 seem to raise the quality level of wines containing lower % level of alcohol. When alcohol % rises, the influence of bound SO2 deminishes.

Reflection

In retrospective, the most difficult part I found was to determine when to stop investigating features or combinations of features and when to move on. For me it is not an exact science and it took me some time to decide that there was nothing more to discover, although later on I sometimes needed to revisit the topic.

What went well was following the univariate, bivariate and multivariate approach. This helped me to focus and build up the story I wanted to tell. What also worked out well was my decision to calculate bound SO2 from free and total SO2. There was a stronger correlation with bound SO2 and quality then with the total/free SO2 and quality. What did surprise me was how the relation looks (with the dip).

Still, I think that wine quality can not be captured so easily by the features that were given. Wine is a complex product with much more nuances in taste and scent.

For future work I would like to have the a finer graded rating like the Robert Parker 100-point scale to see if the distribution of the wine quality is normal. Also I expect it will more insight the correlation between quality and the other features. Using the original scores by the three experts instead of one average score would already add to more granularity.
